This falls under the category of machine learning and specifically, the subfield of unsupervised learning. Therefore, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the update equations of the algorithm, which involves optimization and numerical methods, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also mentions the use of stochastic variants, which falls under the category of optimization and control, making cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the performance of the algorithm in experiments, which falls under the category of computational neuroscience and neural engineering, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category as well.
